BORRELIOSIS, RELAPSING FEVER - ISRAEL: BACKGROUND
*************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
See Also
Borreliosis, relapsing fever, soldiers - Israel 20000423112029
Date: Sun, 23 Apr 2000 20:40:24 +0300
From: Stephen A. Berger, M.D. <mberger@post.tau.ac.il>

The following background information on relapsing fever in Israel was
abstracted from GIDEON http://www.cyinfo.com:
Israel:
- Tick-borne infection is due to _Borrelia persica_, and is most often
acquired in caves and bunkers.
13 cases were reported in 1951 (0.98/100,000); 45 in 1952; 42 in 1953; 15
in 1954; 22 in 1955; 42 in 1956; 8 in 1957; 30 in 1958; 57 in 1959; 57 in
1960 (2.69/100,000).
20 cases were reported in 1961; 17 in 1962; 20 in 1963; 16 in 1964; 4 in
1965; 7 in 1966; 29 in 1967; 15 in 1968; 5 in 1969; 3 in 1970 (0.10/100,000).
Three cases were reported in 1971; 7 in 1972; 4 in 1973; 8 in 1974; 8 in
1975; 10 in 1976; 8 in 1977; 6 in 1978 10 in 1979; 15 in 1980 (0.39/100,000).
13 cases were reported in 1981; 16 in 1982; 11 in 1983; 16 in 1984; 11 in
1985; 9 in 1986; 9 in 1987; 7 in 1988; 6 in 1989; 12 in 1990 (0.26/100,000).
Nine cases were reported in 1991; 0 in 1992; 2 in 1993; 3 in 1994; 7 in
1995 (0.13/100,000); 5 in 1996; 2 in 1997; 10 in 1998; 7 in 1999.
- A single fatal case (1973) was reported during 1954 to 1995.
- The local vector, _Ornithodoros tholozani_ is widely distributed in the
northern highlands, coastal plain and Negev desert. Approximately 10% of
caves in Israel are infested.
--
Stephen A. Berger, M.D.
